# WLED API Atomic Operations Rule

## ❌ NEVER: Separate API Calls for Power/Brightness + Colors

**Problem:** Sending power-on/brightness separately from gradient colors creates a gap where WLED shows restored colors before gradient is applied, causing visible color flashes.

```swift
// ❌ DON'T: Two separate API calls - causes color flash
await updateDeviceState(device) { ... isOn = true }  // Call 1: {"on": true}
await applyGradientStopsAcrossStrip(...)  // Call 2: {"seg": [...]}
// Gap between calls → WLED shows restored colors → Color flash!
```

**Why:** WLED processes each API call immediately. Between calls, WLED may restore its own state (colors from memory), causing a visible flash before gradient is applied.

---

## ✅ ALWAYS: Atomic API Calls - Combine Power/Brightness with Colors

**Solution:** Include `on` and `bri` in the FIRST chunk of per-LED upload, so everything happens in ONE atomic operation.

```swift
// ✅ DO: Single atomic API call - no color flash
await applyGradientStopsAcrossStrip(
    device,
    stops: persistedStops,
    brightness: device.brightness,  // Include brightness
    on: true  // Include power-on
)
// Single call: {"on": true, "bri": 255, "seg": [{"i": [...]}]}
// No gap → No color flash!
```

**Why:** WLED receives everything in one request, processes atomically, preventing any gap where restored colors can appear.

---

## ✅ ALWAYS: Brightness 0% = Device Off

**WLED Behavior:** WLED treats brightness 0% as "off" (`on: false`). Always handle this correctly.

```swift
// ✅ DO: Handle brightness 0% as device off
if brightness == 0 {
    await updateDeviceState(device) {
        var dev = $0
        dev.isOn = false  // CRITICAL: Turn device off
        dev.brightness = 0
        return dev
    }
    return
}

// ✅ DO: Include on=true when restoring brightness from 0%
if wasOff && brightness > 0 {
    await applyGradientStopsAcrossStrip(
        ...,
        brightness: brightness,
        on: true  // CRITICAL: Turn device on
    )
    devices[index].isOn = true  // CRITICAL: Update local state
}
```

**Why:** WLED's API treats `bri: 0` as `on: false`. If we don't handle this, UI state becomes out of sync with device state.

---

## ✅ ALWAYS: State Synchronization

**Critical:** Always update `isOn` state based on brightness value to prevent UI bugs.

```swift
// ✅ DO: Synchronize isOn with brightness
let shouldBeOn = brightness > 0
await applyGradientStopsAcrossStrip(
    ...,
    brightness: brightness,
    on: shouldBeOn ? true : nil  // Include on state
)

await MainActor.run {
    devices[index].brightness = brightness
    devices[index].isOn = shouldBeOn  // CRITICAL: Sync state
}
```

**Why:** Prevents UI showing device as "on" when brightness is 0%, or "off" when brightness > 0%.

---

## ✅ ALWAYS: Power-On with Gradient Pattern

**When turning device on with persisted gradient:**

```swift
// ✅ DO: Skip separate updateDeviceState, include on in gradient
if isTurningOn, let persistedStops = gradientStops(for: device.id), !persistedStops.isEmpty {
    // Skip updateDeviceState - include on in gradient instead
    await applyGradientStopsAcrossStrip(
        device,
        stops: persistedStops,
        brightness: device.brightness,
        on: true  // CRITICAL: Include power-on
    )
} else if isTurningOn {
    // No gradient - use simple power update
    await updateDeviceState(device) { ... isOn = true }
} else {
    // Turning off
    await updateDeviceState(device) { ... isOn = false }
}
```

**Why:** Prevents color flash by combining power-on with gradient in single API call.

---

## ✅ ALWAYS: Brightness Changes with Gradient Pattern

**When changing brightness with persisted gradient:**

```swift
// ✅ DO: Re-apply gradient with brightness, include on state
if brightness == 0 {
    // Turn device off
    await updateDeviceState(device) { ... isOn = false, brightness = 0 }
    return
}

if hasPersistedGradient {
    await applyGradientStopsAcrossStrip(
        device,
        stops: persistedStops,
        brightness: brightness,
        on: brightness > 0 ? true : nil  // CRITICAL: Include on state
    )
    devices[index].isOn = brightness > 0  // CRITICAL: Sync state
} else {
    // No gradient - include on state in brightness update
    let stateUpdate = WLEDStateUpdate(
        on: brightness > 0 ? true : nil,
        bri: brightness
    )
    devices[index].isOn = brightness > 0  // CRITICAL: Sync state
}
```

**Why:** Ensures colors remain visible and state stays synchronized.

